node.text:
After doing "Super Tanker" 8B+ and Atrésie Assis 8A+ I went just a few meters down the hill to the next bloc and got a quick ascent of "Le Dernier Fléau" 8C (8B+) and also climbed that same sitstart into the top of Gourmandise, which hasn't been done yet I think? I suggest "Le Premier Fléau" as a name and 8B+ as a grade 😁😂. I already had done the higher start of those two boulders a couple of days ago ("Gourmandise Raccourci" and "Traphouse Raccourci"). It doesn't change the grade or the climb very much but it was a cool challenge! 
Also got to do the two classics "Tristesse" 7C (flash) and "Big Golden" 7C+. Thanks for the good day outside @yannick_flohe @chrisschweiger @janhojer @urs.thecoach and @martin_schlageter. 

@patagonia_climb @petzl_official @tenayaclimbing @cafekraft_nuernberg @fazabrushes @frictionlabs #stylefirst #carrotsforpower

Whoever bolts a line has the right to make it his project, so nobody else is allowed to try it until it's freed. Every project has a tag at the first bolt to mark it as a project. 
This route here was bolted by a friend and he didn't make it an open project. Nonetheless someone ignored the project rule and just went and did it, although that person got caught and confronted trying the project. 
Today I probably did the second ascent of this route (after the wrongful first ascent) and I'd say it's around 8b+.

node.text:
Don't forget to @fazabrushes the holds after climbing! 
Good training day outside with @jenya_kazbekova, @kraftfactory and Tim. 
Routes in order of climbing:
- warmup 7a
- Steep Mud 7c+
- Father and Son 8c (retro onsight)
- Sonic Excess 8b+ (retro flash)
- 2x Father and Son (double lap)
- Hellboy 8a+
- Father and Son (brushpoint) 

I personally think Father and Son felt more like 8b+ to me. Especially compared to some old school 8c's here in the Frankenjura. But either way an amazing route!

node.text: Thanks to @moritz.perwitzschky for the spot and the good session. Another @f.knaub test piece that got forgotten about. It's located in a nature reserve as many boulders and climbing areas are, so please be considerate when going climbing to ensure that those places don't get closed. Especially now when traveling to different countries is not happening, there will be a lot more people in local spots. Please make sure to impact those places as little as possible. "In urban life you don't even know what time of year it is because you go from one box to another, wake up, open a box of cereal, go into your metal box, spend all day in your glass and steel box, looking at a box; when you get home and you're knackered and you've whacked a little box in a microwave, you turn on the box and eventually get carried out in a box."
From 'Losing Eden' by Lucy Jones. 

Very interesting book illustrating why our minds need the wild, what impact nature has on our mental health and why 'shinrin-yoku' (forest bathing) has healing effects on depression and anxiety. 
With other words: go out, enjoy nature and breath fresh air. And hug a tree if you feel like it. It won't hurt, but it might help. 😉🌱

node.text:
Olympics part #5

2020. I think nobody really foresaw what last year had waiting for us. 
I started the year with the full Olympic preparation. I went speed climbing 3 times a week for 2 months straight and didn't improve the tiniest bit in my eyes. I went to Japan with the German team in February when we first heard about a virus called covid. A couple of weeks later I found myself in the UK competing at the CWIF. All of a sudden covid was getting a lot more serious and the CWIF was my last comp for a while. I took the last flight back to Germany. The atmosphere at the airport was apocalyptic and like nothing I'd ever seen before. All comps got canceled and eventually the Olympics did too. 
Believe it or not but the first thing I felt was a huge relief. Already in March I was so fed up with the gym and the comps I couldn't have imagined to keep going any longer. 
As soon as the Olympics were postponed I didn't set foot into any gym anymore for more than 2 months. March was the last time I touched the speed wall for the whole year. 
I spent most of the lockdown time climbing in the Frankenjura and in summer I also did a few successful trips to France with @jenya_kazbekova climbing Bibliographie. 
I have learned a very valuable lesson during this period of time. Motivation is EVERYTHING. Without motivation fitness and strength are not very useful. 
All the gym training the previous winter felt very draining for me and I started wondering whether or not it was still the right decision for me to compete at the Olympics if they'd happen. By the end of 2020 I had no idea what to do. 
Rock climbing was limited due to multiple lockdowns, I didn't feel very motivated to hit the gym to train for 3 disciplines and I was doubting if I wanted to represent our sport on the big stage. I had come to understand that not even the Olympics were immune towards financial and political influence. I was beginning to wonder if the athletes really were at the center of the biggest sports event on Earth.

node.text:
9b+? 9c? 
What is the difference and how do you know which grade to give? 
At the beginning I thought the number of days you invest in a climb is the best indicator of how hard it must be. Therefore I thought trying Bibliographie for 60 days must be harder than anything I've climbed before. When the word spread that I did the route people immediately started speculating. 
I always had the feeling that 9c might not be the appropriate grade for the route, but I felt some pressure from the climbing world, which was already saying that it must be 9c if it took me 60 days. 
I also didn't have a very good feeling for the grade anymore in the end, because I simply changed my beta so many times, I had such long breaks on the route and I was struggling to compare it with other routes I did. I underestimated how much of a difference it makes to know you have the right beta. On Bibliographie I thought I had good beta until I came back a season later to completely change it again. And that happened twice. So in the end I probably spent the bigger part of 60 days figuring out beta, changing it again and not being sure that I can do it. 
I became more and more convinced that it had to be harder than anything I'd ever done before. 
When @steghiso and a few others started trying they found new beta for both cruxes. Both betas I hadn't tried when I was working on the route. I asked myself how can that be? I spent so many hours on just a few square meters of rock, I should have seen every option. I realized at some point I was so convinced that I had the right beta, that I stopped trying other things. I of course touched the holds of the new beta, but I never actually tried 100% to see if it makes sense. Every time I changed beta on the route it was mainly because I couldn't climb the previous beta. At a certain point I just decided that this will be the beta I'll climb it with and I stopped trying new things. I did succeed in the end, but I have learned something for the future. 
I'm so grateful for your honest opinion Stefano! I agree with 9b+ and now I'll keep looking (with Stefano) for the next potential 9c 😉.

Olympics part #4 

The year 2019 also didn't start very well for me. After my first pulley rupture I didn't climb from mid December 2018 until March 2019. Beginning of March (after a few weeks of easy fingerboarding exercises) I went to Oliana to prepare for the upcoming bouldering world cup season 😅. Surprisingly the first bouldering world cup in Switzerland only a week after Oliana ended with a semifinal! The rest of the bouldering season was an up and down. Half the time I made semis, the other half I didn't. The lead season started off much better with two podiums in Villars and Chamonix. The preparations for the upcoming world championships in Hachioji were in full swing as it was the first chance to qualify for the Olympics. 
In Hachioji my performance in bouldering was a little disappointing with a 25th place and my 75th place in speed was expected so I had to rely on lead. With a second place in lead I secured my spot in the combined qualification (20 people) and I got the chance to climb for an Olympic ticket. 
At the combined qualification I probably had the best bouldering round ever! With 4 tops I won the bouldering round and pretty much secured my Olympic spot! I still was very nervous on the lead wall as I was not sure if a win in bouldering was really enough, but after a good lead performance I proceeded to the combined finals and had my ticket for Tokyo. Another finger injury in finals gave the comp a little bitter aftertaste, but I was incredibly relieved to have achieved my goal.

Olympics part #3: 

The year 2018 didn't start very well for me. Due to a finger injury I didn't climb in January and February. In March I was trying to get back in shape for the upcoming bouldering season. Both bouldering world cups I did in 2018 didn't go well at all. I didn't make semis in either one of them. I did climb my hardest route though back then with "Perfecto Mundo". The lead season went a bit better I'd say. After two finals in Villars and Chamonix I was able to win my first (and only) world cup to date in Briançon. Also the world championships in Innsbruck went well in lead with a second place. Unfortunately, I did rupture one of my hip flexors during the bouldering comp in Innsbruck so the rest of the year was mostly rehab, rock climbing and winning the LaSportiva Legends Only comp in Stockholm! Thankfully I didn't need to use my hip flexors for that one. I did decide to try and qualify for the Olympics though, even though most comps didn't go as expected.

Olympics part #2:

From 2012 to 2017 I hadn't done any official competitions at all. I did a couple of invitational comps and a few CWIF's but that was pretty much it. At the CWIF in 2017 I remember this Swiss guy talking to be and trying to get me back to competing in the world cup circuit. I didn't know who he was and I also didn't know why. A few months went by and the Swiss guy turned out to be the German national coach @urs.thecoach who wanted me to give comp climbing another chance to potentially have a chance to qualify for the Olympics. Back then I was not convinced and definitely not psyched at all. I did get a great opportunity though from the @dav.wettkampfklettern and from @urs.thecoach to compete in a couple of world cups to see how it goes and to see if I liked it. The year 2017 ended with a 7th place at the bouldering world cup in Munich, an unfortunate 8th place at the lead world cup in Arco and a second place at the lead world cup in Kranj. I was intrigued to see if I can do better at comps so I decided to go for a few more comps in 2018. I said I'll decide by December 2018 if I want to give the Olympic qualifications a try.

Back home again. Due to covid restrictions we had to leave Japan rather early. Now it's time to reflect on everything that happened in Tokyo and before to try to learn some valuable lessons for the future. The frustration is still there and the motivation to try hard is gone for the moment. I guess the body and mind will need some time to recover and recharge. 
More thoughts and info about the whole process, the preparation and the comp itself are following soon. 
Now it's time to enjoy some down time though.
